Data Analysis

Conclusions

A random forest model is particularly useful for regression problems that involve non-linear relationships between the dependent and independent variables. And also, provide us an easy way to interpret results by providing the most important features used to explain the independent variable.

Interpreting the results of the random forest model involves understanding various performance metrics and comparing them to assess the model's effectiveness. Let's break down the interpretation of each metric:

Training R^2 Score (Training Coefficient of Determination): Measures the proportion of the variance in the target variable (production) that is explained by the independent variables in the training data. In this case, a score is 0.9403, indicating that approximately 94.03% of the variance in the variable production can be explained by the features in the training data.

Test R^2 Score (Test Coefficient of Determination): Measures the proportion of the variance in the target variable that is explained by the independent variables in the test data. A score of 0.6886 suggests that approximately 68.25% of the variance in the production is explained by the features in the test data. A high score indicates that the model generalizes well to unseen data.

MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error): MAPE measures the average magnitude of the percentage error between the predicted production values and the actual production values in the test data. A MAPE of 0.3662 indicates that, on average, the model's predictions deviate from the actual production values by approximately 36.62%.

RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): RMSE measures the average magnitude of the errors between the predicted production values and the actual production values in the test data. An RMSE of 671.67 indicates that, on average, the model's predictions deviate from the actual production values by approximately 671.67 mmcf (million cubic feet).

Mean Cross-Validation Score: The mean cross-validation score provides an estimate of the model's performance on unseen data by averaging the R^2 scores from cross-validation folds. A mean cross-validation score of 0.5967 suggests that the model performs consistently well across different subsets of the data.

Additionally, we can see the top 5 features that explain the production are:

  • proppant volume (0.19674)
  • tvd (ft) (0.12385)
  • youngs modulus (0.08620)
  • operator_operator 14 (0.08105)
  • md (ft) (0.04643)

In summary, based on the provided results, the random forest model demonstrates strong performance in terms of R^2 scores, MAPE, RMSE, and cross-validation score. Even though there is still room for improvement, with the available data the model shows relatively high predictive accuracy and generalization ability, making it a promising model for predicting production.
